    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "A scanning tunneling microscope maps individual atoms. Move the tip one ten-billionth of a meter closer. The current jumps by a factor of seven.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Why Moving a Tip 1 Angstrom Closer Changes Tunneling Current by 7",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.91,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 7.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Binnig and Rohrer at IBM Zurich in 1981: a sharp metal tip held 5 angstroms above silicon. Lower it 1 angstrom. Current multiplies by roughly 7. Raise it 1 angstrom. Current divides by 7. That factor is how they saw single atoms.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "Create"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 16.67,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 18.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Moving a conductor closer should gradually increase current \u2014 a smooth, roughly linear change. Here a step smaller than an atom multiplies current by seven. Why so dramatic?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
        "headline": "Moving a conductor closer should gradually increase current. Here a 1-angstrom step multiplies current by 7. Why does a change smaller than an atom produce such a dramatic response?",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.12,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 27.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Classical reasoning: current depends on how many electrons can cross the gap. Halving the gap roughly doubles the current. A one-angstrom step is small \u2014 surely a small change gives a small result.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "Create"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.96,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 37.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "But these electrons do not cross the gap. The gap is a vacuum barrier the electrons cannot classically cross. They tunnel \u2014 and the tunneling probability falls exponentially with barrier width.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.3,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 47.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "The exponential is doing the work, not the distance.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE MECHANISM",
        "headline": "Tunneling decays as\ne to the minus 2 kappa d",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.93,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 54.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "The wavefunction leaks into the vacuum barrier as an exponential decay. The probability of finding the electron on the far side falls as e to the minus 2 kappa d, where d is the gap width and kappa is about 1 per angstrom for typical metals. Each angstrom of extra gap multiplies current by e squared \u2014 about 7.4.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 21.58,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 67.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "This means the current does not grow linearly as the tip approaches. On a log scale, current versus distance is a straight line with slope minus 2 kappa. That linearity \u2014 on a log scale \u2014 is the signature of the exponential.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.92,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 78.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "And that exponential is what sees atoms.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE IMPLICATION",
        "headline": "The exponential reads\nsingle-atom bumps",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.27,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 85.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "An atom protruding 1 angstrom above its neighbors is 7 times closer to the tip than the flat surface. So it carries 7 times more current. The microscope does not image atoms directly \u2014 the exponential amplifies the height difference into a current ratio large enough to measure.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "An atom protruding 1 angstrom above its neighbors is 7 times\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B10.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 17.63,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 95.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Without the exponential decay of the wavefunction, no tip would ever resolve a single atom. The entire resolution mechanism is quantum \u2014 tunneling probability amplified by the exponential.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.23,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "t_start": 104.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "A worked example.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE EXAMPLE",
        "headline": "Tip over silicon at 5 angstroms",
        "dek": "(illustrative)"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 1.25,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "t_start": 111.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 19,
      "narration_text": "Work function 4 eV gives kappa of 1.02 per angstrom. Gap of 5 angstroms: current I-naught. Gap of 6 angstroms: current I-naught divided by 7.4. Gap of 4 angstroms: current 7.4 times I-naught. An atom sticking 1 angstrom above its neighbors carries 7 times more current than the flat surface beside it. That atom is now visible.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 25.86,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B13.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B13.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "t_start": 130.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "A step smaller than an atom multiplies current by 7 because the tunneling probability decays as an exponential. Linear changes in distance produce exponential changes in current. That is why the STM sees atoms.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Each angstrom of gap multiplies current by e-squared ~7. The exponential of quantum tunneling gives the STM its atomic resolution.",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stm-exponential/mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.468,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stm-exponential/clips/B14.mp4",
